The envelope protein domain III (ED3) viral epitope on the DENV surface is organized into a complex polyhedral pattern39 with alternating clusters of trivalent or pentavalent ED3 sites. By connecting the clusters of ED3 sites linearly, we determined that a star shape, consisting of an interior pentagon connected to five exterior triangles, would provide an optimal multivalent scaffold (Fig. 1a). The viral diameter of DENV is 50 nm (ref. 39) and vector distances were measured using PyMOL. The distance between adjacent trivalent–trivalent clusters was 15.1 nm and the distance between adjacent trivalent–pentavalent clusters was 14.1 nm. The following equation was used to calculate the orthodromic distances needed to design the scaffold:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
